w:r.w:t: The Furry Fandom, and fandoms alike, while they have many positive reasons to be part of them, have their struggles with accessibility to convenient resources for both creators or participants. In Furry, there are a wide array of specialties that people can chose to engage in, with regards to their interests; Artwork,

Making, Model Artists, Content Creators, Musicians, and so much more. Such specializations require the use of modern web apps in order to share their creations or market them to people in the fandom who may be interested, but each of these have their drawbacks.

Lack of organization, lack of transparency in commissions, poor communication channels, poor curation of algorithms and content filtering, and the limited customization for either a creator or users to best express who they are.

So with all that said, why not make a place for everyone to be, both creators and users, where either can thrive in a medium that allows for a great social atmosphere, customizations for creators to build their profiles and users alike, and building a place that is process oriented to deliver the best experience
for both the creators and the users. Let us wipe the slate clean, just like the open and barren landscape of the Sahara to build something fresh
that has not been explored yet
and connect the fandom in a more convenient, fun, transparent,
utilizing interfaces such as force-directed graph user interfaces to curate your content filtering.
Project Sahara is a culmination of hobbyist

bringing their professional expertise together to make a medium that brings together some of the best attributes that can be found in webapps currently used by others in the Fandom today. While there are many great features found in the current webapps today, there are a slew of issues encountered which make it challenging for a user.
-Properly curating their audience, or to curate their feed on the content they want to see.
-Communication having its pitfalls if one party or the other decides not to properly communicate during a commission process, which can leave the artist or commissioner hanging in the balance.
-Poor User Interface design which can lead to confusing navigation of site pages or
-Sites not having integrations where it makes it convenient for both the user and creator to hold the process in one centralized space start to finish, including the communication channels.
-No Traceability of Commissions where updates and status could be tracked
-No review systems to review an creators overall performance and project management overtime (or also not having a method to appeal bad reviews to protect creators from bad actors)
-No fun UI elements that allow for creative ways to navigate around the sites.

Based on a lot of these common pitfalls in the current landscapes of websites, our goal is to bring a solution to most of these gaps to create an experience that is fun and transparent to the user and the creator, and a multifaceted approach on social media that eliminates the negative Pidgeon hole effect that directs negative content users may not want to engage in and interact with, and a more focused propagation of content based on the
Any individual who uses the medium as either a creator, or a user who will be conducting forms of exchanges with creators, events, social blogs, postings.
